The system provides a "safe-cam action" and unbelievably smooth double action only trigger stroke, fast to fire in critical defensive situations. Many lower cost compact semi-autos on the market today do not have firing pin blocks in their design. - Kahr's two patents covering the offset recoil lug and the trigger bar attachment allow Kahr's barrel to fit lower in the frame, and since there is no hammer, the shooter's hand is further up the grip resulting in less felt recoil and quick follow-up shots.

title: For Sale:  Winchester "Wingo" Arcade rifle - EXTREMELY RARE
postcontent:
Most people have never even seen one of these. Only about 4 are known to be outside of the Winchester collection - there were less than 50 ever made. Lever action .20 cal shotgun - looks like a .22 lever action with vented rib. Works, has all internal wiring. A thumbnail picture would not be of any use to you -too small - but will take pictures for serious buyers. Here is what I found on the Internet:

Wingo was an experimental indoor wing shooting sport invented by the Winchester-Western Division of the Olin Corporation in the early 1970s.[1] The only Wingo facility built was in San Diego, California and was in operation during 1971. It was a family friendly sport enjoyed by men, women and children. Competing teams were organized into leagues. Many area businesses formed teams to compete with one and another. Individual play was also available. The building was purpose built for the new sport and luxurious in it's appointments. It contained a service and concession area, a restaurant and two sunken lounges with seating and color slide shows of sporting activities. It had a large parking lot and a very large sign with the "Wingo" logo only. This created a natural curiosity about what it was to passing motorists. The cost of a 10 shot game was one dollar. Popular Science published an article in the February 1971 issue titled ”Indoor Wingshooting Is Here” about Wingo.
The equipment consisted of a bank of 18 machines that created 4-inch-diameter (100 mm) hollow spheres of ice. One of the original machines is in the collection of the Buffalo Bill Historical Center. The player had a custom-made .20 calibre lever action shotgun that was about the same size and weight as a .22 calibre rifle. The choice of calibre was to prevent players from bringing their own .22 calibre shells from outside. The Wingo shot shell was brass with a crimped end and a "w" stamped on the base. It was 24.81mm in length, 5.36mm in case diameter and 6.94mm in rim diameter at base. It was loaded with 119 lead pellets of #12 shot and produced a 30" pattern at 50 feet. The rimfire ammunition was produced by Olin in boxes of 30 or 36 shells with the Wingo logo. The gun was tethered to the shooting bench to prevent it from being pointed toward spectators and to facilitate the wiring for the internal microphone that detected when the gun was fired. The gun was also wired to only fire when the ice target was launched. The gun weighed in at 5.5 pounds and was 38″ in length. It had a "Kwik-Point" scope for quick and easy targeting. Only about 20 of these smooth barrel guns were made and they are now very rare collector's items.

I got this straight from Winchester. I sold one of these for Winchester and it went for $2,500.00 to a Winchester collector. I have a letter of authenticity from Winchester for this rifle

Call me at REDACTED if you have any questions

title: For Sale:  Remington Nylon 76 .22 LR The rarest of the rare!
postcontent:
I am offering for sale the ONLY LEVER ACTION RIFLE ever made by Remington Arms Co.. This is also the Holy Grail for collectors of the Nylon Series of rifles from the early to mid 1960's. These are so rare that this is the only one I have ever seen in person and I have been to I can't count how many ginstores across the country and close to 1000 gunshows. I have been asked by colloectors if I have ever seen one and when I have told them that I have one they go nuts just to see it. I am the original owner of the rifle. This was a birthday present for my 10th birthday in 1964. This rifle has been shot maybe a 1000 times, I am really not sure. It still works great it is very good condition for it's age and it has a Bushnell Scope on it. The scope for this rifle is usually a necessity as the screw that held the rear iron sites was so thin that it would usually strip out after two or three adjustments. It is a tube loader from the butt staock. It holds 14 rounds in the tube and one in the chamber. When these Nylon Rifles were introduced they were touted as being next to indestructable and they are close this one has been all over the country and to Canada many times in it's life. I DO NOT NEED TO SELL THIS RIFLE so my price is firm and I am only looking to sell no trades etc. I do not need any more guns or equipment. I am at the point of reducing the things that I have to simplify my life. I am putting it out there for sale to see if there is someone who really wants this for their collection. 
Asking price is $1000.00
  FTF and local only prefered if you are willing to pay for shipping and FFL transfer costs on top of the cost of the rifle then we can talk, you must have a valid Ohio Drivers License or CCW or other valid form of ID. Must be willing to sign a bill of sale. Buyer will have to meet me at my place of choice. Cash only. 
Please respond via email on Armslist and leave your phone number or text number and I will get back to you within 12 hours at the most. 
Thanks for looking.
